<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="34">
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BCD2FA80-79F3-46AD-856C-5BE9DF05C735" class="Holocephali" family="Chimaeridae" genus="Hydrolagus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hydrolagus Gill 1862:331" order="Chimaeriformes" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Hydrolagus</taxonomicName>
is one of two genera found within the family Chimaeridae. Species in this family are typically characterized as having short fleshy snouts that are bluntly pointed at the tip, elongate bodies tapering to a whiplike tail with an elongate filament, and are uniform brown, gray, or black in color with the possibility of white spots or stripes (Didier, 2004). There is very little difference between 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BCD2FA80-79F3-46AD-856C-5BE9DF05C735" class="Holocephali" family="Chimaeridae" genus="Hydrolagus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hydrolagus Gill 1862:331" order="Chimaeriformes" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Hydrolagus</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Holocephali" family="Chimaeridae" genus="Chimaera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chimaeriformes" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Chimaera</taxonomicName>
, the other genus within this family, other than the presence (in 
<taxonomicName class="Holocephali" family="Chimaeridae" genus="Chimaera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chimaeriformes" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Chimaera</taxonomicName>
) or absence (in 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BCD2FA80-79F3-46AD-856C-5BE9DF05C735" class="Holocephali" family="Chimaeridae" genus="Hydrolagus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hydrolagus Gill 1862:331" order="Chimaeriformes" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Hydrolagus</taxonomicName>
) of an anal fin. The anal fin is located anterior to the ventral caudal fin and is only separated from it by a small notch and can be very subtle, making it sometimes difficult to distinguish the two genera (Bigelow and Schroeder, 1953; Didier, 1995, 2004; pers. obs.).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="34">
Comprising 17 of the 24 known species within this family, species of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BCD2FA80-79F3-46AD-856C-5BE9DF05C735" class="Holocephali" family="Chimaeridae" genus="Hydrolagus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hydrolagus Gill 1862:331" order="Chimaeriformes" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Hydrolagus</taxonomicName>
are found in every ocean, except the Arctic and Antarctic (Didier, 2004), with the greatest diversity known from the western Pacific. The only species of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BCD2FA80-79F3-46AD-856C-5BE9DF05C735" class="Holocephali" family="Chimaeridae" genus="Hydrolagus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hydrolagus Gill 1862:331" order="Chimaeriformes" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Hydrolagus</taxonomicName>
known from eastern South Pacific is 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:A9515375-350D-4C4B-B6BA-B58BE59BAC9B" class="Holocephali" family="Chimaeridae" genus="Hydrolagus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hydrolagus macrophthalmus de Buen 1959:186" order="Chimaeriformes" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrophthalmus">Hydrolagus macrophthalmus (de Buen, 1959)</taxonomicName>
, a poorly known species described from two specimens collected from off Valpraiso, Chile. The holotype (Figure 1), which was thought to be lost due to a tsunami that partially destroyed the museum it was previously contained in, was rediscovered and it is now part of the collection at the Museo Nacional de Historia Natural in Santiago, Chile (MNHNC P. 7282). There have also been specimens of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:A9515375-350D-4C4B-B6BA-B58BE59BAC9B" class="Holocephali" family="Chimaeridae" genus="Hydrolagus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hydrolagus macrophthalmus de Buen 1959:186" order="Chimaeriformes" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrophthalmus">H. macrophthalmus</taxonomicName>
collected from off Peru and these are used for comparisons in this study (Chirichigno, 1968; Didier, unpubl. data). Morphometrics and morphological features confirm that 
<taxonomicName class="Holocephali" family="Chimaeridae" genus="Hydrolagus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chimaeriformes" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="alphus">Hydrolagus alphus</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is different from 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:A9515375-350D-4C4B-B6BA-B58BE59BAC9B" class="Holocephali" family="Chimaeridae" genus="Hydrolagus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hydrolagus macrophthalmus de Buen 1959:186" order="Chimaeriformes" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrophthalmus">Hydrolagus macrophthalmus</taxonomicName>
. This is the second new species of chimaeroid from the Galapagos Islands (Barnett et al., 2006) and adds a third species to the diversity of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BCD2FA80-79F3-46AD-856C-5BE9DF05C735" class="Holocephali" family="Chimaeridae" genus="Hydrolagus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hydrolagus Gill 1862:331" order="Chimaeriformes" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Hydrolagus</taxonomicName>
in the eastern tropical Pacific.
</paragraph>
